"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110569","Department for International Trade","false","2019-04-17","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) was set up in July 2016. There have been no non-disclosure agreements signed with employees working for DIT or UK Export Finance (UKEF) since this date.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-04-17T16:25:03.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110569/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110569/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-04-09","Department for International Development: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many non-disclosure agreements his Department has entered into with departmental staff in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","242810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110570","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-16","<p>No such non-disclosure agreements have been agreed by the Department during this timeframe.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-04-16T14:31:51.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110570/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110570/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","Department of Health and Social Care: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many non-disclosure agreements his Department has entered into with departmental staff in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","242811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110571","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-16","<p>In February 2015, Cabinet Office published new guidance on non-disclosure agreements. This guidance requires a minister to approve the use of a non-disclosure agreement, and for government departments to hold a record of using such agreements.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>DWP has not entered into any non-disclosure agreements in the four years since February 2015 and our policy is not to use these agreements.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to February 2015, DWP did not centrally hold a record of the use of non-disclosure agreements and the information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-04-16T14:43:21.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110571/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110571/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-09","Department for Work and Pensions: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many non-disclosure agreements her Department has entered into with departmental staff in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","242812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110572","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-15","<p>The UK National Screening Committee advised that Faecal Immunochemical Test (FIT) is a more sensitive and accurate test than guaiac faecal occult blood test (FOBt), and that more bowel cancers could be detected, and recommended that FIT should replace the currently used FOB test.</p><p> </p><p>Full replacement of the current FOBt with FIT across all Hubs in the NHS Bowel Cancer Screening Programme is planned for summer 2019.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-04-15T12:59:51.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110572/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110572/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","Bowel Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timescale is for the introduction of the faecal immunochemical test for the bowel cancer screening programme in England.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","242932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110573","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-15","<p>No year contains 53 weeks. This perceived issue of their being 53 weeks in a year arises where a landlord charges rent weekly on a Monday and, because of the way the calendar falls every 5 or 6 years, seeks 53 rent payments in a year, with the 53rd payment in part covering the tenancy for the first few days of the following year.</p><p>Universal Credit payments are designed to mirror the world of work, with monthly payments reflecting the way many working people are paid. This model of monthly payments allows claimants to take responsibility for budgeting their own income and helps prepare them for getting back to work. The Money and Pension Service can provide debt advice and money guidance to claimants if they need support managing their monthly Universal Credit payments.</p><p>We are aware of a separate issue with respect to the way the calculation in the Universal Credit regulations converts a weekly liability into a monthly allowance. The conversion is achieved by multiplying the weekly rent by 52 and then dividing by 12. This effectively means one day’s rent a year (two days in a leap years) are not covered by UC. We are currently considering whether this formulation around weekly rents, and potentially other weekly amounts in the UC calculation, should be amended.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-04-15T14:48:11.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110573/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110573/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-09","Universal Credit: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking to ensure that universal credit adequately supports social housing tenants paying rent weekly to meet their obligations in relation to the 53 week year.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","242667"
