"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110818","Department for Education","false","2019-04-15","<p>The admissions system works well and the vast majority of parents will be allocated a place at one of their preference schools. In 2018, 91.0% were offered their first choice primary school and 97.7% received offers from one of their top 3, while 82.1% were offered their first choice secondary school and 93.8% received offers from one of their top 3.</p><p>We are not complacent and want to continue to ensure fair access to a good school place for every pupil. That is why we routinely keep the admissions system under review and seek feedback from stakeholders on the health of the system.</p><p>As announced in the Home Office Domestic Abuse White Paper, we are currently considering whether changes to the School Admissions Code would be helpful in supporting the admission of the most vulnerable pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-04-15T15:30:45.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110818/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110818/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-04-09","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he has taken to conduct a review of school admissions policy; and what plans he has to do so in future.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","242854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110819","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>We have not compiled such information, although information on the treatment and facilities used by each local authority will be recorded within the Waste-Data-Flow system (<a href="http://www.wastedataflow.org/" target="_blank">http://www.wastedataflow.org/</a>) that local authorities use to provide information on waste collection and management.</p><p> </p><p>Some local authorities use local facilities, others transport it outside of their areas. This is a commercial matter for each local authority, and each local authority must do what achieves the best value for money for its residents.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T13:52:43.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110819/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110819/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many local authorities (a) deal with locally arising waste in their area and (b) export it outside their area.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110820","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>Necessary regulation has already been approved by Parliament and will come into effect when the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-16T13:45:48.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110820/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110820/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Gases: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps is he taking to ensure that all European regulations on gases are being continued after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110821","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount of obligated WEEE received for treatment at AATFs (tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount of non-obligated WEEE received at AATFs for treatment (tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total (tonnes)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>486,403.968</p></td><td><p>77,426.524</p></td><td><p>563,830.492</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>505,398.630</p></td><td><p>74,667.937</p></td><td><p>580,066.567</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>501,050.257</p></td><td><p>158,319.669</p></td><td><p>659,369.926</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>494,407.835</p></td><td><p>184,834.761</p></td><td><p>679,242.596</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>509,809.170</p></td><td><p>134,811.069</p></td><td><p>644,620.239</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>529,058.633</p></td><td><p>132,069.321</p></td><td><p>661,127.954</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>592,428.047</p></td><td><p>126,999.022</p></td><td><p>719,427.069</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>534,582.034</p></td><td><p>118,592.058</p></td><td><p>653,174.092</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2018</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>501,885.359</p></td><td><p>61,409.832</p></td><td><p>563,295.191</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The above table details the quantity of UK electronic waste received at Approved Authorised Treatment facilities for treatment and subsequent recycling for the period 2010 to 2018. This data only reflects electronic waste received at sites which have been approved as part of the WEEE regulations to issue WEEE evidence in support of the financial obligations placed on EEE producers.</p><p> </p><p>There are other waste operators, who will hold a permit issued under the Environmental Permitting regulations who will also be treating and recycling WEEE delivered to them outside of the WEEE producer Responsibility system. Such operators are not required under their data reporting requirement to provide specific WEEE data.</p><p> </p><p>Defra make a substantiated estimate on this additional WEEE treated and recycled, when reporting the UK position to the EU. The substantiated estimate is for an additional 270,000 tonnes per annum of WEEE being treated and recycled in addition to amounts detailed in the above table.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T14:01:19.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110821/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110821/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Electronic Equipment: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many tonnes of electronic waste were recycled in each year in the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110822","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>There has been no assessment undertaken on which local authorities have been most successful in collecting electronic and electrical waste for recycling and none is planned.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-16T13:47:52.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110822/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110822/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Electronic Equipment: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of which local authorities have been most successful in collecting electronic and electrical waste waste for recycling.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110823","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>There are currently 1,855 local authority household waste recycling centres approved as Designated Collection Facilities under the UK Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment (WEEE) Regulations 2013.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T12:46:04.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110823/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110823/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Electronic Equipment: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many centres for recycling electronic and electronic waste there are in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110824","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>The UK has a high degree of food security, built on access to a range of sources including strong domestic production and imports from other countries. This will continue to be the case when we leave the EU, with or without a deal. The size and diversity of the industry is a key factor in enabling the food sector to remain resilient to food supply chain disruptions.</p><p>The Government has well established ways of working with the food industry to minimise potential disruption. This includes working with Defra’s long established Food Chain Emergency Liaison Group (FCELG), which allows Government and industry to work together to plan for and respond to any food supply disruption. This industry group’s membership is drawn from across the agri-food chain sector and includes other relevant government departments, Devolved Administrations and agencies.</p><p> </p><p>On food prices, we have observed that the most important drivers of change in the cost of food are global food commodity prices, exchange rates and oil prices. This will continue to be the case once the UK has left the EU.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","242751","2019-04-16T15:20:01.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110824/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110824/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what contingency plans the Government has in place to support vulnerable people in the event food prices rise significantly in the event of the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","242750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110826","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>The UK has a high degree of food security, built on access to a range of sources including strong domestic production and imports from other countries. This will continue to be the case when we leave the EU, with or without a deal. The size and diversity of the industry is a key factor in enabling the food sector to remain resilient to food supply chain disruptions.</p><p>The Government has well established ways of working with the food industry to minimise potential disruption. This includes working with Defra’s long established Food Chain Emergency Liaison Group (FCELG), which allows Government and industry to work together to plan for and respond to any food supply disruption. This industry group’s membership is drawn from across the agri-food chain sector and includes other relevant government departments, Devolved Administrations and agencies.</p><p> </p><p>On food prices, we have observed that the most important drivers of change in the cost of food are global food commodity prices, exchange rates and oil prices. This will continue to be the case once the UK has left the EU.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","242750","2019-04-16T15:20:01.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110826/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110826/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to (a) minimise food disruption and (b) consider the possible effects food shortages could have on vulnerable groups in the event of the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","242751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110827","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>The current 2013 Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment (WEEE) Regulations are based on producer responsibility requiring producers to pay for the environmentally sound collection, treatment and recycling of electronic products when they become waste. The WEEE Regulations have contributed to high levels of collection, treatment and recycling of electrical waste since 2014. Last year, producers financed the collection of 493,323 tonnes of household WEEE.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Resources and Waste Strategy sets out that we will consult on changing the WEEE producer responsibility regime by the end of 2020 as part of the strategy to increase resource efficiency and the adoption of circular economy principles. Measures to stimulate recycling of electrical and electronic equipment will consider how to reward producers for designing and selling more resource efficient products or services.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T13:07:10.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110827/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110827/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Electronic Equipment: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what new incentives is he considering to stimulate the recycling of electronic and electrical waste.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110828","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-17","<p>UK Research and Innovation (UKRI) funds high quality research and innovation as part of the Government’s wider ambition to increase the UK’s total R&amp;D investment to 2.4% of GDP by 2027. UKRI works in partnership with universities, research organisations, businesses, charities, and government to create the best possible environment for research and innovation to flourish.</p><p> </p><p>Current examples that relate to generating energy from waste include £1.7m from Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council through the Global Challenges Research Fund for <a href="https://gtr.ukri.org/projects?ref=BB%2FS011439%2F1" target="_blank">a project led by the University of Leeds</a> to facilitate the production of biogas, clean water, and the recovery of nutrients, from nutrient rich waste.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-04-17T15:43:22.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110828/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110828/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Waste: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what investment his Department has made in university and other institutions researching into energy from waste with heat recovery.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110829","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Coalition Government removed targets for local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>Information on local authority recycling rates in England can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-collected-waste-management-annual-results" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-collected-waste-management-annual-results</a></p><p> </p><p>and here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/766014/LA_and_Regional_Spreadsheet_201718_rev2.xlsx" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/766014/LA_and_Regional_Spreadsheet_201718_rev2.xlsx</a></p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-16T15:00:51.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110829/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110829/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many local authorities are successful in meeting Government targets for recycling.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110830","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>We are working with Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) to build the existing evidence base and to understand the most cost effective ways for LAs to achieve consistent recycling collections. WRAP has also been working across a number of key areas to develop resources, guidance and practical examples to assist LAs and organisations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-16T15:15:20.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110830/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110830/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what level of investment his Department is making in new research on the better management of local authority waste management.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110831","Treasury","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Government-established Payment Systems Regulator (PSR) is closely monitoring developments within ATM provision. The PSR regulates LINK, the scheme which runs the UK’s ATM network and has used its powers to hold LINK to account over LINK’s commitments to preserve the broad geographic spread of the ATM network.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, LINK has put in place specific arrangements to protect free-to-use ATMs more than 1 kilometre away from the next nearest free-to-use ATM and has also enhanced its Financial Inclusion Programme, tripling the funding available to ATMs in the most deprived areas of the UK. LINK has also announced new additional premiums to safeguard the presence of free-to-use ATMs in remote and deprived areas.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-04-15T11:17:22.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110831/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110831/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-04-09","Cash Dispensing: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps is he taking to seek to  ensure that ATM operators maintain no charge access to machines in rural areas throughout the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","242726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110832","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Government set out in the 25 Year Environment Plan, published in January 2018, its commitment to eliminate all avoidable plastic waste and to work towards all plastic packaging placed on the market being recyclable, reusable or compostable by 2025. Our Resource and Waste Strategy was published in December 2018 and contains details of measures that will help to achieve this.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently consulting on a suite of proposals that will lead to an increase in the supply and demand for secondary materials. These include reforming the UK packaging producer responsibility system, the introduction of a deposit return scheme (DRS) for drinks containers in England, and a tax on plastic packaging with less than 30% recycled content, all subject to consultation. These measures will provide a strong incentive for producers to design and make plastic packaging that uses less virgin materials and is more easily recyclable.</p><p> </p><p>We want to increase the quantity and quality of material that is collected and recycled. To achieve this, we are consulting on requiring all waste collection authorities to collect the same core set of dry materials from households across England. We want to make recycling clearer and easier so that everyone knows exactly what they can put in the recycling bin, whether at work or at home.</p><p> </p><p>The consultations setting out the Government’s proposals and measures referred to above were published on 18 February and can be found here: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/environmental-quality/resource-and-waste-and-plastic-packaging-tax-consu-1/" target="_blank">https://consult.defra.gov.uk/environmental-quality/resource-and-waste-and-plastic-packaging-tax-consu-1/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>There may be times when a ban is appropriate as part of a wider strategic approach. We have already banned the sale of plastic microbeads, consulted on banning plastic drinking straws, stirrers and cotton buds, and are assessing the impact of banning other single-use plastic items.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T13:12:59.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110832/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110832/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Plastics: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce the amount of non-recyclable plastic; and what initiatives he is rolling out on recycling.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110833","Home Office","false","2019-04-23","<p>Information on Project AIDANT (the series of multi-agency operational intensifications to tackle modern slavery and human trafficking led by the National Crime Agency) can be found in the 2018 Annual Report on Modern Slavery which can be found here: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/749346/2018_UK_Annual_Report_on_Modern_Slavery.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/749346/2018_UK_Annual_Report_on_Modern_Slavery.pdf</a></p><p>It should be noted that the number of potential victims includes victims encountered overseas during the operations who do not qualify for referral to the UK National Referral Mechanism or Duty to Notify. The data held is reported individually by police forces and law enforcement agencies and may therefore not reflect the full picture of NRM referrals as it is not possible to determine from the NRM database directly which referrals relate to AIDANT activity.</p><p>Data on the number of potential victims detained prior to identification is not held centrally.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-04-23T13:28:46.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110833/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110833/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-09","Human Trafficking: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 30 April 2018 to Question 137048 on Human Trafficking: Sexual Offences, how many potential victims of trafficking or modern slavery were identified through Project AIDANT activity in (a) 2017, (b) 2018 and (c) 2019 to date; how many of those potential victims were detained prior to identification; and how many of those potential victims were referred to the National Referral Mechanism.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","242819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110834","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-12","<p>NHS Property Services has responsibility for a large mixed estate of approximately 3000 properties, across approximately 3 million square metres, and with approximately 7000 individual tenancies. Occupiers range from general practitioners, providers, arm’s length bodies and many other organisations supporting health and social care services. With such a large and diverse portfolio that is subject to constant change both as business as usual and in support of transformational change, parts of the estate do become under-utilised or vacant. In terms of recorded vacant space this varies as space is re-occupied/disposed, new space becomes vacant or new buildings come into the portfolio.</p><p> </p><p>The overall average figures for occupancy levels for the years where data is available is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2017/18 Average</p></td><td><p>2018/19 Average</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>88.07%</p></td><td><p>89.31%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In terms of the ‘average occupancy levels’, NHS Property Services does not hold the data for 2015/16 and 2016/17 as property information was captured on numerous different platforms many of which were not able to report on occupancy levels.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","242863","2019-04-12T13:54:03.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110834/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110834/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","NHS: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the current occupancy levels for properties owned by NHS property services.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","242862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110835","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-12","<p>NHS Property Services has responsibility for a large mixed estate of approximately 3000 properties, across approximately 3 million square metres, and with approximately 7000 individual tenancies. Occupiers range from general practitioners, providers, arm’s length bodies and many other organisations supporting health and social care services. With such a large and diverse portfolio that is subject to constant change both as business as usual and in support of transformational change, parts of the estate do become under-utilised or vacant. In terms of recorded vacant space this varies as space is re-occupied/disposed, new space becomes vacant or new buildings come into the portfolio.</p><p> </p><p>The overall average figures for occupancy levels for the years where data is available is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2017/18 Average</p></td><td><p>2018/19 Average</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>88.07%</p></td><td><p>89.31%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In terms of the ‘average occupancy levels’, NHS Property Services does not hold the data for 2015/16 and 2016/17 as property information was captured on numerous different platforms many of which were not able to report on occupancy levels.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","242862","2019-04-12T13:54:03.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110835/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110835/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","NHS: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the average occupancy levels for properties owned by NHS property services were in (a) 2015-16, (b) 2016-17, (c) 2017-18 and (d) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","242863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110836","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-15","<p>Annual statements are produced for all individuals who owe a debt to the Legal Aid Agency which is secured by way of the statutory charge.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-04-15T15:54:08.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110836/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110836/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-09","Legal Aid Agency: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has plans to ensure the Legal Aid Agency provides individuals with annual statements of the amount they owe to the Agency.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","242778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110837","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-15","<p>Where legally aided clients successfully gain or retain an asset as a result of the publicly funded legal assistance they receive, they should repay the cost of their legal aid.</p><p> </p><p>The rate in the statutory charge is currently set at 8%, the same as the Judgment Debt Interest Rate. It was reviewed in 2008/09.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-04-15T16:07:36.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110837/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110837/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-09","Legal Aid Agency: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of reducing the daily rate of interest charged by the Legal Aid Agency to individuals who owe that Agency money.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","242779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110838","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-23","<p>Since its establishment in 2014, the British Business Bank has facilitated over £27.6m to 684 Scottish businesses in the 2014/15 financial year (FY), over £81.9m to 1,484 Scottish businesses in FY 2015/16, over £267.5m to 1,895 Scottish businesses in FY 2016/17, and over £291.6m to 2,881 Scottish businesses in FY 2017/18. These figures include Start-up loans from 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Since launching in 2012, the BBB Start-Up Loans programme specifically (which became part of the Business Bank in 2014) has issued over 3,500 loans in Scotland, averaging £7,200 each and worth over £25m in total.</p><p> </p><p>The British Business Bank is a Limited Partner for the three largest VC funds in Scotland (SEP, PenTech, and Panoramic) with over £80m invested in innovative, high growth companies.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-04-23T16:32:07.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110838/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110838/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","British Business Bank: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what level of support the British Business Bank has provided to businesses in Scotland in each year since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","242959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110839","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency holds current data on the number of people with 12 penalty points or more on their driving record. On 9 April 2019 the number of people with 12 penalty points or more who have entitlement to drive is 11,105.</p><p>Some of these drivers will have already served a disqualification which expired before the penalty points attributed to the offence(s).</p><p>Some will be drivers who had cited ‘exceptional hardship’ to the court after they had reached 12 penalty points under the ‘totting-up’ provisions. In these circumstances the disqualification may either be avoided or significantly reduced.</p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency is the holder of the record of all GB fixed penalties and court ordered endorsements, but is not responsible for setting them or influencing court imposed sentences.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-04-15T12:50:08.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110839/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110839/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many holders of UK driving licences with 12 points or more on their licence have been allowed to continue driving in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","242864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110840","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>Government committed in its 2017 manifesto to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services, recognising the important role post offices play to service their communities. Government investment led to the most stable network in generations, with over 11,500 branches across the UK, the largest retail network in the country.</p><p> </p><p>Number of open Post Offices since 2016 is as follows;</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>End of March 2018</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>End of March 2017</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>End of March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ellesmere Port and Neston Constituency</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West England</p></td><td><p>1119</p></td><td><p>1117</p></td><td><p>1116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>11547</p></td><td><p>11659</p></td><td><p>11643</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T16:01:06.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110840/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110840/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many post offices have closed in each of the last three years in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston (b) North West England and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","242865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110841","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-16","<p>Other than the nominal £1.00 payment, included as standard in the NHS Licence Agreement, no payments have been received by the Department from third parties for use of the National Health Service logo over the last three years.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-04-16T14:35:32.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110841/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110841/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","NHS: Logos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will detail payments made by third parties in each of the last three years in return for use of the NHS logo.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","242866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110842","Home Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>The application process for the EU Settlement Scheme is straightforward and user-friendly, and it is accessible on any smartphone, tablet or computer using internet browsers.</p><p>There are multiple ways to have identity documents checked, including using the EU Exit: ID Document Check app or by posting identity documents to the Home Office. We have also opened 50 locations nationwide where applicants can have their passport scanned and verified.</p><p>The ID document scanning service is provided at the discretion of each local authority. The Home Office would encourage as many local authorities as possible to offer the service, and we continue to work with local government bodies across the UK to increase the provision of this service by local authorities.</p><p>The viability and cost of offering the ID document scanning service in each location is a matter for each local authority. Charges for using the service, payable directly to the local authority, can be set to cover the costs of providing the service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","242868","2019-04-15T11:47:28.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110842/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110842/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-09","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the viability of an ID scanning location in Glasgow for applicants to the EU Settlement scheme.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","242867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110843","Home Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>The application process for the EU Settlement Scheme is straightforward and user-friendly, and it is accessible on any smartphone, tablet or computer using internet browsers.</p><p>There are multiple ways to have identity documents checked, including using the EU Exit: ID Document Check app or by posting identity documents to the Home Office. We have also opened 50 locations nationwide where applicants can have their passport scanned and verified.</p><p>The ID document scanning service is provided at the discretion of each local authority. The Home Office would encourage as many local authorities as possible to offer the service, and we continue to work with local government bodies across the UK to increase the provision of this service by local authorities.</p><p>The viability and cost of offering the ID document scanning service in each location is a matter for each local authority. Charges for using the service, payable directly to the local authority, can be set to cover the costs of providing the service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","242867","2019-04-15T11:47:28.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110843/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110843/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-09","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost of ID document scanning services is at facilities in (a) Cunmock, (b) Kilmarnock and (c) Edinburgh.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","242868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110844","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-15","<p>The total amount spent by the Ministry of Justice on probation services in England and Wales for the years requested is set out in a summary table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Probation Expenditure, nominal*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£851,700,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£804,500,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£832,400,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>£819,800,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>£874,600,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Figures have been rounded and show actual costs</p><p> </p><p>The expenditure prior to 2014/15 is for Probation Boards and Trusts. From 2014/15 onwards, responsibility for providing probation services transferred to the new National Probation Service (NPS) and 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs). The cost increase in 2014/15 was for transition and mobilisation costs of setting up the NPS and CRCs, as well as closing down Probation Trusts, as part of the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2019-04-15T16:50:01.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110844/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110844/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-09","Probation: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 4 April 2019 to Question 238275 on Probation: Private Sector, what estimate he has made of the cost to his Department of probation services in each year between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","242720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110845","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>This is a devolved matter and the information provided therefore relates to England only.</p><p> </p><p>The Resources and Waste Strategy was published on 18 December 2018.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-16T12:37:11.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110845/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110845/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has plans to publish a strategy for recycling waste.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","242711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110846","Wales Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>I have recently discussed the Stronger Towns Fund on several occasions with Cabinet colleagues in different forums.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2019-04-15T09:08:33.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110846/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110846/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-04-09","Stronger Towns Fund: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 4 April 2019 to Question 239184 on 4 April on Stronger Towns Fund: Wales, on what date he held those meetings; and if he will publish the attendees at those meetings.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","242721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110847","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The management of the Post Office network, including Post Office community status branches, is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore as ked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T16:01:38.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110847/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110847/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Post Office Branches classified as having community status (a) have been closed, (b) are operated by a temporary Sub Postmaster, and (c) are operated through an outreach service in (i) Scotland, (ii) Wales, (iii) Northern Ireland, and (iv) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110848","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Temporary closures across the UK is an operational matter for the Post Office. is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T16:04:06.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110848/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110848/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Post Office branches under the Network Transformation Programme (a) have been converted and subsequently closed, (b) have moved to another location and subsequently closed, (c) have yet to receive new investment because the original branch that received funding has now ceased trading in (i) Scotland, (ii) Wales, (iii) Northern Ireland, and (iv) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110849","Treasury","false","2019-04-23","<p>The information requested is not readily available, as such the information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-04-23T15:48:43.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110849/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110849/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-04-09","Revenue and Customs: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, much the HMRC spent on hiring private venues in Glasgow for meetings with individual taxpayers in the financial year 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","242869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110850","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Payments to branches are an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T16:05:43.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110850/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110850/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Post Office branches are receiving overscale payments, and what the value of those overscale payments is in each of the last five years, in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland, and (d) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110851","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>Post Office Limited are required to notify customers when opening new branches rather than to carry out a consultation. This is in accordance with the ‘Principles of Community Engagement on Changes to the Post Office Network’ agreed with Citizens Advice, the independent statutory consumer watchdog.</p><p> </p><p>The document is available at this link: <a href="http://corporate.postoffice.co.uk/sites/default/files/Principles%20of%20Community%20Engagement_June%202018.pdf" target="_blank">http://corporate.postoffice.co.uk/sites/default/files/Principles%20of%20Community%20Engagement_June%202018.pdf</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T16:08:27.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110851/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110851/answer","Principles of Community Engagement_June 2018.pdf","PO - Principles of Community Engagement ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110851/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons his Department did not conduct a consultation on opening new Post Office branches under the terms of the New Network Locations.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110852","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>Government has invested over £2 billion in the Post Office since 2010. Funding has been split between subsidy funding to support branches that are not economically viable and investment funding to modernise the post office, including transforming branches and franchising some directly managed branches. The split for the current funding package between April 2018 to March 2021 is £210 million in investment funding and £160 million in subsidy.</p><p> </p><p>Network Development programmes, including the New Network Location Programme, are funded from the current funding provided to Post Office Limited from Government.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Thus, the precise allocation of funding to different programmes is an operational matter for Post Office Limited and subject to commercial confidentiality.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:52:44.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110852/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110852/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the cost of the Post Office’s New Network Location Programme is, and how that programme is funded.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110853","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The Department has made no such assessment because the management of the network is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:53:48.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110853/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110853/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the New Network Location Programme on existing post office branches.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110854","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The management of the network is an operational matter for the Post Office. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:55:03.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110854/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110854/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many New Network Locations have opened in each year of the New Network Location Programme, and how many are planned to open in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland, and (d) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110855","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Any plans to convert Pay Zone branches into Post Office Locations throughout the UK is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:55:49.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110855/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110855/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Pay Zone branches are planned to be converted into Post Office Locations in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland, and (d) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110856","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Operators of the Post Office Network throughout the UK is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:56:25.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110856/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110856/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many operators operate more than 10 locations in the Post Office Network in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland, and (d) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110857","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The contractual relationship between Post Office Limited and postmasters is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:57:00.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110857/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110857/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department has had with the Post Office on resolving the matter of sub-postmasters who are unable to leave their branch due to inability to meet criteria or find an alternative location.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110858","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The contractual relationship between the Post Office and Royal Mail is an operational matter for Post Office Limited. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:57:54.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110858/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110858/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Office: Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the status of the contract between the Post Office and Royal Mail; and what steps his Department is taking to help ensure the continuation of that contract.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110859","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over £2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. The health and wellbeing of postmasters is of course a priority for Government. I have therefore asked Alisdair Cameron, the Group Interim Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the hon Member on this matter. A copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-04-16T15:58:33.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110859/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110859/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-04-09","Post Offices: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure the health and wellbeing of sub-postmasters who remain in their Post Office branch because no viable alternative has been found.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","242891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110860","Department for International Development","false","2019-04-16","<p>Since 2011, DFID has benefited 10 million primary and nearly 6 million secondary students in Pakistan. This support is mainly focussed on schools in the Punjab, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Sindh with our two largest sector reform programmes operating in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Punjab. In the last 3 years DFID Pakistan has spent the following on each education project:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Project</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/2017</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/2018</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/2019</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>202328 - Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Education Sector Programme</strong></p></td><td><p>£36.4m</p></td><td><p>£34.2m</p></td><td><p>£28.9m</p></td><td><p><strong>£99.5m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>202491 - Transforming Education in Pakistan</strong></p></td><td><p>£3m</p></td><td><p>£3m</p></td><td><p>£2m</p></td><td><p><strong>£8m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>202697 - Punjab Education Support Programme II</strong></p></td><td><p>£68.4</p></td><td><p>£64.1m</p></td><td><p>£41.6m</p></td><td><p><strong>£174.1m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>204277 - Ilm Ideas Education Innovation Programme II</strong></p></td><td><p>£3.3m</p></td><td><p>£5.5m</p></td><td><p>£8.3</p></td><td><p><strong>£17.1m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>300238 - Sindh Education Non-State Actors (SENSA) </strong></p></td><td><p>£3.1m</p></td><td><p>£3.6m</p></td><td><p>£1.8m</p></td><td><p><strong>£8.5m</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-16T16:21:56.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110860/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110860/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-04-09","Pakistan: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has allocated to each educational project in Pakistan in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","242673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110861","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-12","<p>The Government set out its ambition for improving sexual health and wellbeing in A Framework for Improving Sexual Health in England, which was published in 2013. This can be viewed online at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/a-framework-for-sexual-health-improvement-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/a-framework-for-sexual-health-improvement-in-england</a></p><p> </p><p>We consider the ambitions set out in the Framework remain relevant. However, we continue to keep this matter under review.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-04-12T14:02:47.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110861/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110861/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","Genito-urinary Medicine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the need for a sexual health action plan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","242752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110862","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-17","<p>To address the increase in syphilis diagnoses in England, Public Health England (PHE) is developing a Syphilis Action Plan, with recommendations for PHE and partner organisations, to improve detection, surveillance and clinical management. PHE plans to publish its Syphilis Action Plan in spring 2019.</p><p>To reduce the transmission of sexually transmitted infections (STIs), including gonorrhoea and syphilis, PHE launched the ‘Protect Against STIs’ health promotion campaign in 2017/18 to promote condom use and positive sexual relationships among 16 to 24-year olds. This campaign can be viewed at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/protect-against-stis-use-a-condom/home" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/protect-against-stis-use-a-condom/home</a></p><p>Additionally, HIV Prevention England has been contracted to deliver a HIV prevention programme aimed at gay, bisexual and other men who have sex with men, black Africans, and other black minority ethnic populations. This programme promotes condom use and awareness of sexually transmitted infections including gonorrhoea and syphilis. More information on this programme can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hivpreventionengland.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.hivpreventionengland.org.uk/</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","242754","2019-04-17T12:30:54.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110862/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110862/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","Sexually Transmitted Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government is taking to tackle the increase in cases of (a) syphilis and (b) gonorrhoea; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","242753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110863","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-17","<p>To address the increase in syphilis diagnoses in England, Public Health England (PHE) is developing a Syphilis Action Plan, with recommendations for PHE and partner organisations, to improve detection, surveillance and clinical management. PHE plans to publish its Syphilis Action Plan in spring 2019.</p><p>To reduce the transmission of sexually transmitted infections (STIs), including gonorrhoea and syphilis, PHE launched the ‘Protect Against STIs’ health promotion campaign in 2017/18 to promote condom use and positive sexual relationships among 16 to 24-year olds. This campaign can be viewed at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/protect-against-stis-use-a-condom/home" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/protect-against-stis-use-a-condom/home</a></p><p>Additionally, HIV Prevention England has been contracted to deliver a HIV prevention programme aimed at gay, bisexual and other men who have sex with men, black Africans, and other black minority ethnic populations. This programme promotes condom use and awareness of sexually transmitted infections including gonorrhoea and syphilis. More information on this programme can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hivpreventionengland.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.hivpreventionengland.org.uk/</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","242753","2019-04-17T12:30:54.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110863/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110863/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-09","Sexually Transmitted Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment his Department has undertaken on the reasons for increasing rates of (a) syphilis and (b) gonorrhoea.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","242754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110864","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>Like all wild birds, swifts, swallows and martins as well as their nests and eggs are offered robust protection under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. Individuals convicted of an offence could face up to six months in prison or an unlimited fine, or both.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-15T13:02:16.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110864/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110864/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Birds: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the current protections in place for swifts, swallows and martins.","false","Biography information for Alberto Costa","South Leicestershire","Alberto Costa","242873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110865","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>The department does not hold this information.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T10:56:16.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110865/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110865/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Railways: Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many rail replacement bus services were utilised in (a) 2010, (b) 2017 and (c) 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110866","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Department continually monitors the rail user experience, including passengers’ satisfaction with rail services. We set a range of challenging satisfaction targets for operators in Franchise Agreements, including on how delays are handled, and if these targets are missed, operators must invest in improvements. We expect train companies to manage periods of disruption in a way that minimises the impact on passengers and maintains a high quality service.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T10:44:25.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110866/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110866/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Railways: Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of rail replacement bus services on rail service standards; and what assessment he has made of the effect of those services on the rail user experience.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110867","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>Government recognises the economic and environmental benefits of rail freight and is committed to transporting more goods by rail. The Government has published a Rail Freight Strategy to provide a stable policy framework to enable rail freight to grow and achieve its potential to unlock these benefits. Transporting more goods by rail freight brings environmental and congestion benefits, and the Government is committed to working with the rail freight industry to support its continued success.</p><p> </p><p>To support future growth of the rail freight industry the Secretary of State also confirmed that Government intends to continue investment in improving the rail freight network in Control Period 6 (2019-2024) as part of their funding settlement.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T11:24:29.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110867/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110867/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent steps his Department has taken to increase the use of rail for freight.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110868","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>Train operators are obliged to sell the most appropriate through fare based on the information the passenger gives them. We are aware that for some journeys it can be cheaper to purchase two or more tickets for individual parts of the route than a through ticket for the entire journey. Going forward, we are considering how best to reform the fares and ticketing system, removing complexity and perverse pricing.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T12:56:17.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110868/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110868/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department taken to (a) simplify (b) encourage the purchase of split rail tickets.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110869","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>On average, at Fratton Station, staff were available to assist customers, on the platform for 154hrs per week, and in the booking office for 141hrs per week, in 2018. Data is unavailable for 2010.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T12:48:37.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110869/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110869/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Fratton Station: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many hours per week on average staff were available in person to assist customers at Fratton rail station in (a) 2010 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110870","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-15","<p>There were 280 staff employed at railway stations in Hampshire in 2010 and 304 in 2018, an increase of close to 10 per cent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-15T12:44:38.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110870/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110870/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-09","Railway Stations: Hampshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many railway station staff were employed to work at stations located in Hampshire in (a) 2010 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","242965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110871","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>We are aware of credible reports of the presence of the Rapid Support Forces, as well as other security forces, in the vicinity of protests in Khartoum. We have consistently urged the Sudanese authorities to refrain from using force against civilians.</p><p>​</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-15T12:53:57.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110871/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110871/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-09","Sudan: Rapid Reaction Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Rapid Defence Force has been deployed on the streets of Khartoum.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","242674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110872","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 3 April 2019 to PQ 213909.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-04-15T11:00:59.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110872/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110872/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Bovine Tuberculosis: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many herds in each of the following badger cull areas of (a) Gloucestershire and (b) West Somerset were tested with interferon gamma in each years from 2010 to 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","242675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110873","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 5 February 2019 to PQ 213910.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-04-15T12:20:11.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110873/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110873/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Bovine Tuberculosis: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many interferon gamma tests were conducted on each of the herds in (a) Gloucestershire  and (b) Somerset; and how many cattle tested positive in each herd in each year from 2010 to 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","242676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110874","Home Office","false","2019-04-11","<p>There are now 50 locations nationwide where applicants can have their pass-port scanned and verified.</p><p>Details of the service and the locations where this service is available can be found on Gov.UK at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/eu-settlement-scheme-id-document-scanner-locations</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-04-11T13:29:13.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110874/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110874/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-09","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 2 April 2019 to Question 236270 on Immigration: EU Nationals, at what locations applicants for the EU Settlement Scheme can have their passport scanned.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","242688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110875","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-16","<p>The migration of Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager commenced in August 2016.</p><p> </p><p>From August 2016 to 10 April 2019 we have migrated 1.12m Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager. As claimants may have had multiple Social Fund debts, the number of debtors will be significantly lower than this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We continue to build in the appropriate checks and balances to ensure that Social Fund cases migrate correctly. Where an incorrect balance has been identified we take steps to correct the case.</p><p> </p><p>Corrections can be applied for different reasons, which mean we cannot estimate the volume of adjustments made to date.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","242716 ; 242717","2019-04-16T14:29:35.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110875/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110875/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-09","Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many social fund loan cases have been moved from the social fund computer system to debt manager since 2016.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","242715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110876","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-16","<p>The migration of Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager commenced in August 2016.</p><p> </p><p>From August 2016 to 10 April 2019 we have migrated 1.12m Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager. As claimants may have had multiple Social Fund debts, the number of debtors will be significantly lower than this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We continue to build in the appropriate checks and balances to ensure that Social Fund cases migrate correctly. Where an incorrect balance has been identified we take steps to correct the case.</p><p> </p><p>Corrections can be applied for different reasons, which mean we cannot estimate the volume of adjustments made to date.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","242715 ; 242717","2019-04-16T14:29:35.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110876/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110876/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-09","Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will estimate how many social fund loan cases moved from the social fund computer system to debt manager show an incorrect outstanding balance.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","242716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110877","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-16","<p>The migration of Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager commenced in August 2016.</p><p> </p><p>From August 2016 to 10 April 2019 we have migrated 1.12m Social Fund debts onto Debt Manager. As claimants may have had multiple Social Fund debts, the number of debtors will be significantly lower than this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We continue to build in the appropriate checks and balances to ensure that Social Fund cases migrate correctly. Where an incorrect balance has been identified we take steps to correct the case.</p><p> </p><p>Corrections can be applied for different reasons, which mean we cannot estimate the volume of adjustments made to date.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","242715 ; 242716","2019-04-16T14:29:35.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110877/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110877/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-09","Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department plans to take steps to rectify incorrect outstanding balances on social fund loan cases on debt manager.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","242717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110878","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Working Group has not had an operational budget since its inception however going forward it will be supported to undertake some of its activities in working with communities. Members do not receive remuneration and undertake their roles on a voluntary basis.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-04-15T14:48:59.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110878/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110878/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-09","Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the annual budget is for the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group; and whether members of that group receive remuneration.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","242904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110879","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-04-15","<p>The AMHWG was set up in 2012. In 2018 we launched the first open recruitment process to appoint members. During this process 24 women applied to be independent members. The Working Group is led by Ms Akeela Ahmed OBE, founder of a civil society platform dedicated to amplifying women’s voices, and we have appointed Ms Asma Ali, Data Protection Officer and Solicitor for the Police Service of Scotland. Ms Iman Abou Atta is an ex-officio member, as Director of Tell MAMA.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-04-15T14:46:32.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110879/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110879/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-09","Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many women have applied to become members of Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group (a) since it was first set up and (b) in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","242905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110880","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-04-15","<p>The process of appointing new members was managed by the Ministry of Housing, Communities, and Local Government.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-04-15T14:44:50.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110880/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110880/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-09","Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether an independent body is involved in the process of appointing new members of the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","242906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110881","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-04-30","<p>The Government has been working hard for some time on minimising the impact on trade flow in the event that the UK were to leave without a deal, this includes meeting with the Welsh ports, and we recognise the importance of trade between Wales and Ireland. As set out in the Political Declaration, the UK and EU have both agreed that the future economic partnership should be based on the principle of no tariffs, fees, charges or quantitative restrictions across all sectors.</p><p>The UK and Irish governments have also been clear that maintaining the CTA is a top priority. British citizens in Ireland and Irish citizens in the UK will continue to be able to live and work in each other’s countries, and to access healthcare, education, social welfare and benefits including state pensions.</p><p>In a no deal scenario, the Government will introduce customs easements to ensure that the flow of imports into Wales will be as smooth as possible. A pragmatic approach has also been agreed with the secretariat of the Common Transit Convention for managing movements under that convention. For exports the impact depends on handling in Dublin, so the Government is working with all stakeholders to keep potential disruption to a minimum.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2019-04-30T15:01:47.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110881/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110881/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-04-09","Borders: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of a hard border between Wales and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","242791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110882","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>The Environment Agency (EA), like the rest of the public sector, is playing its part in reducing the national deficit and delivering more with less. Both Defra and the EA recognise the challenges that reduced funding bring and the EA is adapting its approach accordingly.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015/16, the EA launched a new approach to partnership working to help it deliver more effectively and efficiently. Its 5 Point Approach to Salmon management (published in 2016), is a good example of how it is working with like-minded organisations to deliver shared priorities.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-04-16T11:13:38.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110882/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110882/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Salmon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the Environment Agency’s ability to carry out the management of salmon stocks as a result of recent reductions in funding levels.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","242776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110883","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-16","<p>The EA continues to fulfil its statutory duties in relation to fisheries.</p><p> </p><p>Freshwater fisheries regulation is a core role and unique activity that only the EA can fulfil. The EA makes resources available to deliver current regulations, including the rod and net licensing system; scheduled reviews of Net Limitation Orders; reviewing and consolidating fishery byelaws; making new byelaws where this is necessary to protect stocks; and determining fishery management permit applications.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-04-16T11:18:45.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110883/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110883/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the Environment Agency ability to carry out all its statutory duties in relation to fisheries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","242777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110884","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>Following the transition of services from Royal Mail Group to Capita in October 2017, Capita’s performance fell short of expected levels. However, due to the close monitoring that has been in place through the governance arrangements, Capita’s performance has improved and is now operating closer to the contracted levels.</p><p> </p><p>There is a robust governance framework in place that provides Cabinet Office with the relevant oversight to manage the contract. This framework enables Cabinet Office to monitor performance and continuous improvement but also provides an escalation route for any issues that may be encountered throughout the term of the contract. The Governance model includes an advisory board, called the Royal Mail Pension Scheme Governance Group, which is made up of representatives from stakeholders of the scheme including Union (on behalf of members), employer and Pensioner representatives</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-04-15T09:54:00.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110884/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110884/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-09","Royal Mail: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of Capita's performance in  administering the Royal Mail Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","242687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110885","Prime Minister","false","2019-04-11","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the press release issued on 9 April 2019 following my meeting with Chancellor Merkel and which is available on the <a href="https://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-meeting-with-chancellor-angela-merkel-9-april-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-meeting-with-chancellor-angela-merkel-9-april-2019</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2019-04-11T08:43:49.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110885/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110885/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2019-04-09","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what the outcomes were of her discussions with the German Chancellor on Tuesday 9th April 2019 on the situation in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","242689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110886","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-04-23","<p>The Online Harms White Paper consultation proposes that the duty of care applies to companies that provide services or tools that allow, enable or facilitate users to share or discover user-generated content, or interact with each other online. It, therefore, would not typically apply to consumer smart devices. Harms suffered by individuals that result directly from a breach of data protection, breach of cyber-security or hacking are also excluded from scope.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Government has taken a number of actions to increase the security of consumer smart devices. In October 2018, DCMS published the Code of Practice for Consumer Internet of Things (IoT) Security to support manufacturers in building strong security into smart products by design. We recognise that further action is needed, and we will soon be publishing a consultation on our regulatory proposals regarding consumer IoT security.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","242935","2019-04-23T11:10:26.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110886/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110886/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-04-09","Internet: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Online Harms White Paper published on 8 April, whether the proposed duty of care applies to (a) internet of things manufacturers, (b) internet of things service providers and (c) electricity companies' smart meters.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","242826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110887","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-04-23","<p>Following the publication of the Online Harms White Paper on 8 April, we are consulting on proposals for the statutory duty of care to apply to companies and other bodies that allow users to share or discover user-generated content or interact with each other online. The consultation, which can be found here (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/online-harms-white-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/online-harms-white-paper</a>) closes on 1 July.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-04-23T11:05:32.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110887/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110887/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-04-09","Internet: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Online Harms White Paper published on 8 April, whether the proposed duty of care applies to those (a) using algorithms in their business and service delivery processes and (b) providing business and consumer services commercially.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","242827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110888","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Government intends to prohibit the hunting of Greenland white fronted goose by removing the species from schedule 2 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. I anticipate that the legislation will be laid this autumn.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to remove the European white-fronted goose from schedule 2 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","242654","2019-04-15T09:15:50.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110888/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110888/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when his Department will publish its response to the consultation on removing the Greenland White-fronted goose from schedule 2 of the Wildlife Act 1981.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","242653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110889","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Government intends to prohibit the hunting of Greenland white fronted goose by removing the species from schedule 2 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. I anticipate that the legislation will be laid this autumn.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to remove the European white-fronted goose from schedule 2 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","242653","2019-04-15T09:15:50.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110889/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110889/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-09","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to remove the European white-fronted goose from schedule 2 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","242654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110890","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-15","<p>There is a range of measures available to the police and local authorities to prevent or respond to dog attacks on livestock. The Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 makes it an offence to allow a dog to be dangerously out of control and this includes in and around livestock. In addition, the Dogs (Protection of Livestock) Act 1953 makes it an offence to allow a dog to worry livestock. The Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 includes specific powers for police and local authorities to take action before a dog becomes dangerously out of control by issuing a warning notice for low level dog related nuisance. The table below provides the number of people prosecuted under the Dogs (Protection of Livestock) Act 1953 for allowing dogs to worry all types of livestock, including sheep, in the last five years for which figures are available. Prosecutions have been made under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 but data is not centrally held on the circumstances of how the dog was dangerously out of control.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Dogs (Protection of Livestock) Act 1953</strong> <strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Prosecuted</strong></p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>232</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","242656 ; 242657","2019-04-15T15:46:26.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110890/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1110890/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, F